Words by taylorfreesolo and jadethemighty // - This week the news was released that our Orca sis Tokitae (Sk'aliCh'elh-tenaut, her Lummi name) has been granted permission by her “owners” to go home to a sanctuary in the Salish Sea. This brings up a lot of feelings because while this is a long fought win, it’s a situation that should never had happened if we all honored our relationships to non-human kin, as the Lummi have - her direct human relatives. Thank you to those at the forefront of that fight (oursacredsea) and we hope her journey home helps us all connect to the greater history of human violence and the future ahead of reparations. We know that road ahead is filled with lots of questions about how she gets home and what that process looks like. There’s also the hurdle, as with anything, of funding. Stay tuned as we are here to help those who are organizing. 

The big other news this week was that in a historic event of collaboration amongst 191 countries, a commitment to protect 33% of the biodiversity on Earth was made at COP15. Another win that has been long fought and championed by many, our dear prospektmiraorg, and Indigenous and rural communities with deep relationship and sacred instructions to protect biodiversity. 

With both these scenarios, we feel a bit of relief for the more the human world, and at the same time we wonder about the other 66% - why not a commitment to try and protect all the biodiversity that’s on the brink of collapse? Is it simply that we’re too little too late in the greater trajectory?

As most of us know, Indigenous Peoples protect 80% of the world’s remaining biodiversity. So , when it comes to this new UN commitment, we sure as hell better see a significant majority of investment go towards Indigenous Peoples as well as a commitment to Indigenous rights. Because, whether it’s our Orca sis or the destruction of old growth forest and other critical biodiversity regions, none of this would have happened if people took Indigenous rights seriously and supported any community, indigenous or not, who lives in deep and direct relationship to the land.

This National Geographic expedition charts a path through the Arctic from Maine to Alaska, retracing the steps of Sir John Frank-lin. Words by freddiewilkinson / photo #2 by snackfarmer / natgeo expedition.studios #LavaSandwich expedition

A confused swell sweeps us out to sea: more like randomized, multifaceted undulations than organized flow. We thrum along at 8 or 9 knots, powered by Australis’s powerful 1963 Gardiner engine, the auto pilot set to 117 degrees.

Each day the temperature grows a little colder and we spend less time on deck. Below, the slosh of human life continues in warm, confined spaces. Twelve people burrowed into 24 meters of steel. We learn the basics to survive at sea as functioning organisms: how to pass each other in shoulder-width passages, and time our trips to the microwave, or the head. And keep a bucket close. 

Not much more than warm toast or white rice goes down our first couple days at sea. Subtle things can set you off. The smell of diesel, or coffee grounds. Too much water in the gut. Once the feeling strikes, it’s already too late.

Our team collectively tries different strategies for dealing with sea-sickness: medication, exercise, diet, movies, alcohol. Kieran prefers to look out on the horizon, gazing out from the pilot house for hours on end. Carla meditates. My lower bunk mate, Joao Lages, spends 23 hours a day in his bunk, staring at he ceiling. As long as he remains still, he doesn’t feel sick, Joao swears — he’s cool.

But perhaps nobody got it worse than volcanic_emma, who would spend her birthday, Thanksgiving night, curled up in a fetal position on floor of the hallway just outside the bathroom, her body wrecked with periodic dry heaves throughout the night.

Words by freddiewilkinson, natgeo expedition.studios writer, guide, story producer and #GillDog master:

We’re slowly coming back to normal life as we depart the Falkland Islands after an unforgettable voyage to the remote, mysterious South Sandwich Islands in the South Atlantic Ocean.

It all began earlier this year, when volcanic_emma decided to answer the siren call of Mt. Michael, a ~ 900 meter unclimbed volcano located on a tiny speck of ash and rock known as Saunders Island. For more than twenty years, volcanologists have speculated about the strange thermal anomaly visible in satellite imagery that seems to emanate from within Michael’s crater. The heat signature, which at times has indicated surface temperatures of more than 1000 degrees C, was suggestive of molten lava close to the Earth’s surface — perhaps even one of nature’s rarest phenomena and volcanologists’ most valuable natural laboratory, an active lava lake. But because the volcanic gases constantly exiting the crater mix with the region’s infamous weather conditions to create a witch’s brew of sulfur dioxide plume, cloud, and storm — getting a clear-eyed look into the crater is virtually impossible from space. And, thanks to Saunders Island’s location, directly downwind of the Drake Passage at 57 degrees south and 1300 nm from the closest port, getting there the old fashioned way is a wee-bit inconvenient. 

You might say Emma’s dream was to explore this uncharted volcano, maybe even “discover” a lava lake. But she (like all good field scientists) prefers another term: ground-truthing. 

What Emma didn’t immediately reveal is that more people have been to the moon than had set foot on Saunders Island… and now we know why. Stay-tuned for  the #LavaSandwichExpedition

Still processing this one and the loss of Hilaree hilareenelson. 

Hils led one of the most intense expeditions of our lives in the Burmese Himalaya.  Everything went wrong and unexpected challenges kept hitting us from every possible angle.  Yes, she was unbelievably strong on the mountain carrying more weight than anyone but it was also the way she carried herself during the hard moments in between…uplifting everyone around her and finding laughter even within the hardship.  She will always be a beacon for how to move through life with grace, grit and love.

Evin değerini bulmak için kullanılan en yaygın yöntemlerden biri, aynı veya benzer muhitteki diğer evlerin değerlerini araştırmaktır. Burada en doğru sonuca ulaşmak için araştırdığınız evlerin, almayı veya satmayı düşündüğünüz konut ile benzer özelliklere sahip olmasına dikkat etmeniz gerekiyor. Aksi takdirde konut değerinde yanlış hesaplamalar yapabilirsiniz. Binanın yaşı, evin cephesi, metrekaresi, kaçıncı katta bulunduğu, binada asansör bulunması gibi faktörler de ev değerini belirlemede büyük önem taşır.
Daire değerini belirleyen aşağıdaki faktörleri de dikkate alarak benzer muhitte bulunan evler ile kendi evinizi daha tutarlı bir şekilde kıyaslayabilirsiniz. Böylece evinizin satış fiyatını hakkında bilgi sahibi olabilirsiniz.

Ev kirası hesaplaması için evin yıllık kira gelirini evin satış bedeline bölmek gerekir. Bir örnek vermek gerekirse evin yıllık kira geliri 12 bin lira, evin satış fiyatı ise 288 bin lira olduğunu kabul edersek evin amortisman süresi 20 yıl oluyor. Kiraya verilecek ev hesaplamalara göre amortisman süresi 20 yıla kadar olan evler için kira bedeli yıllık 12 bin yani aylık 1000 lira olmalıdır.
